To align a row of divs to the right using flex in CSS, follow these steps:
1. Set the container element's display property to `flex`. This will make it a flex container.
2. Set the container element's justify-content property to `flex-end`. This will align all child elements along the end line of the container.
Here is an example code snippet:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <title>Align divs to right using flex</title>
    <style>
      .container {
        display: flex;
        justify-content: flex-end;
        background-color: #f0f0f0;
        padding: 10px;
      }

      .box {
        width: 50px;
        height: 50px;
        margin: 5px;
        background-color: #4caf50;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="box"></div>
      <div class="box"></div>
      <div class="box"></div>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
```

In this example, the `.container` element is set to `display: flex`, and its `justify-content` property is set to `flex-end`. This aligns all child elements (the `.box` divs) along the end line of the container.
